div.head:
The Remarkable Sayings, Apothegms
and Maxims of the Eaſtern Nations;
with Obſervations upon them.

div.p:
               Obſervation. That it is more emphatical in the Perſian;
for the ſame Word that ſignifies to carry or bear,
ſignifies alſo to bear up under, or to ſupport.

The more Men hope, the leſs they obtain;
becauſe hope is often a means not to obtain
what they expect.

Never enquire into things which are to come;
but inform your ſelf of thoſe which are paſt,
in order to improve by them.

Increaſe your Children and your Family;
you do not know that it is on their account you
find wherewith to ſubſiſt.

When Good offers it ſelf to you embrace it;
but reject Evil as ſoon as it appears to ſurpriſe
you.

Men are divided into two Claſſis: The one
find what they ſeek for, and yet are not contented;
the others ſeek and do not find.

All the World cannot ſatisfie a covetous Man;
but, a ſober Man only deſires Bread to ſatisfie
Nature.

Moderation muſt be conſider'd like a Tree;
the Root of which is to be contented; and the
Fruit, to be at reſt.

Whoever gives Council, does all he has to do;
let him who receives it, take care to put it in
execution.

Whoever is in the Service of Princes, and of
great ones, muſt obſerve five things to avoid
giving his Enemies any advantages over him.
He muſt never be ſurpriz'd in a Lie by his Maſter;
he muſt never ſpeak ill of any body before him;
he muſt never diſpute any thing with him; he
muſt never do any thing contrary to his Orders;
and finally, he muſt never reveal the Secret he
has conſided to him.

Good Actions rebound on thoſe who do them;
but the Evil which the Wicked commit is againſt
themſelves.

Great Profits may accrue by Sea Voyages;
but to avoid the danger, the ſafeſt way is not to
Imbark, and to remain a Shore.

By patience we come to the end of all things;
but that is ſuch a Vertue as few Perſons practiſe,
and that too very rarely.
